    <title type="text">Ehud Netzer Publications Available to Public from the BAS</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<span style="font-size: small;"><a
      href="http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/archaeology-today/archaeologists-biblical-scholars-works/ehud-netzer-publications-available-to-public/?mqsc=E3460349&amp;utm_source=WhatCountsEmail&amp;utm_medium=BHDDailyNewsletter&amp;utm_campaign=E3B220">Ehud
      Netzer Publications Available to
      Public<b>&nbsp;</b></a></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b> </b>from the <a
      href="http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/">BAS</a></span><b><br
      /></b></span><br /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">Ehud Netzer, a prominent Israeli archaeologist and the world’s
      leading authority on Herodian architecture, died on October 27, 2010 from a fall at Herodium,
      where he had been digging for 38 years in search of Herod’s tomb. Herod the Great was the
      ancient world’s builder <em>par excellence</em>. Netzer described Herod as “a king
      who lived and breathed the art of construction, deeply understood its ways and, quite simply,
      loved to build.” One might fairly say that Ehud Netzer himself lived and breathed the man and
      the works of Herod.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><span style="font-size: x-small;">In his long career, Netzer
      worked at Herodium, Jericho, Masada and numerous other sites, including Hazor, Sepphoris,
      Caesarea and Jerusalem. A member of <em>Biblical Archaeology Review’s</em>
      editorial advisory board for 30 years, he frequently wrote for the magazine. <a
      href="http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/people-cultures-in-the-bible/people-in-the-bible/herod-the-great-the-kings-final-journey/">In
      February 2013, the Israel Museum in Jerusalem opened a new exhibit on the journeys of two men
      separated by 2,000 years</a>. One was the funeral procession of King Herod the Great; the
      other was the life work of Ehud Netzer.</span><br /><br /><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>In a commemoration of the scholarship of Ehud Netzer, Biblical
      Archaeology Society has made a special collection of his groundbreaking scholarship from the
      BAS Library available for free</strong>. This collection includes the posthumously
      published “<a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=37&amp;Issue=1&amp;ArticleID=7">In
      Search of Herod’s Tomb</a>,” a piece that sits at the heart of the Israel Museum exhibit
      <a
      href="http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/people-cultures-in-the-bible/people-in-the-bible/herod-the-great-the-kings-final-journey/"><em>Herod
      the Great—The King’s Final Journey</em>.</a></span><br
      /><h3><span style="font-size: x-small;">BAS Publications by Herodian Scholar and
      Archaeologist Ehud Netzer (click titles to read)</span></h3><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"> </span><h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=37&amp;Issue=1&amp;ArticleID=7">In
      Search of Herod’s Tomb</a></span></h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>BAR</strong> 37:01, Jan/Feb 2011<br />by Ehud
      Netzer</span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><h2><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=35&amp;Issue=1&amp;ArticleID=9">A
      New Reconstruction of Paul’s Prison</a></span></h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>BAR</strong> 35:01, Jan/Feb 2009<br />by Ehud
      Netzer</span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><h2><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSAO&amp;Volume=2&amp;Issue=1&amp;ArticleID=14">Floating
      in the Desert</a></span></h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><em>Archaeology
      Odyssey</em> 2:01, Winter 1999<br />by Ehud Netzer</span><br /><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"></span><h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=19&amp;Issue=3&amp;ArticleID=7">Uncovering
      Herod’s Seaside Palace</a></span></h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>BAR</strong> 19:03, May/Jun 1993<br />By Barbara
      Burrell, Kathryn Gleason and Ehud Netzer</span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><h2><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=18&amp;Issue=6&amp;ArticleID=2">New
      Mosaic Art from Sepphoris</a></span></h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>BAR</strong> 18:06, Nov/Dec 1992<br />By Ehud Netzer and
      Zeev Weiss</span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><h2><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=17&amp;Issue=6&amp;ArticleID=13">The
      Last Days and Hours at Masada Found at Dan</a></span></h2><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>BAR</strong> 17:06, Nov/Dec 1991<br />By Ehud
      Netzer</span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><h2><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=14&amp;Issue=4&amp;ArticleID=2">Jewish
      Rebels Dig Strategic Tunnel System</a></span></h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>BAR</strong> 14:04, Jul/Aug 1988<br />By Ehud
      Netzer</span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><h2><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=9&amp;Issue=3&amp;ArticleID=2">Herod’s
      Family Tomb in Jerusalem</a></span></h2><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>BAR</strong> 9:03, May/Jun 1983<br />By Ehud
      Netzer</span><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"></span><h2><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSBA&amp;Volume=4&amp;Issue=4&amp;ArticleID=3"><b>BAR</b>
      Readers Restore and Preserve Herodian Jericho</a></span></h2><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"></span><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><strong>BAR</strong> 4:04, Nov/Dec 1978<br />By Ehud
      Netzer</span><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;"></span><span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/people-cultures-in-the-bible/people-in-the-bible/herod-the-great-the-kings-final-journey/">See
      a Biblical Archaeology Society web-exclusive slideshow gallery from the <em>Herod the
      Great—The King’s Final Journey</em> exhibit at the Israel Museum, along with Suzanne F.
      Singer’s exhibit review.</a></span></blockquote>&nbsp; <br
      />]]></content>
